# Projectile Motion

A ball launched at angle $\theta$ with initial speed $v_0$ follows a parabolic
trajectory under gravity. Because gravity only acts vertically, we can treat
horizontal and vertical motion independently.

Here we launch a ball at $\theta = 30°$ with $v_0 = 20\ \text{m/s}$,
$g = 9.8\ \text{m/s}^2$.

```text
1. Decompose initial velocity into components
     vx = v0 · cos(θ) = 20 · cos(30°) = 17.32 m/s
     vy = v0 · sin(θ) = 20 · sin(30°) = 10.00 m/s

2. Apply kinematic equations at time t
     x(t) = vx · t
     y(t) = vy · t − (1/2) · g · t²

3. At the peak, vertical velocity is zero
     vy − g·t_peak = 0    ⇒    t_peak = vy / g ≈ 1.02 s

4. Total flight time (ball returns to y = 0)
     t_flight = 2 · vy / g ≈ 2.04 s

5. Evaluate the trajectory at successive timesteps.
```

The governing equations are:

$$
x(t) = v_0 \cos(\theta) \cdot t
\qquad
y(t) = v_0 \sin(\theta) \cdot t - \tfrac{1}{2} g t^2
$$

